{{NCAATeamFootballSeason |Year=2007 |Team=Missouri Tigers |Image= |Conference=Big 12 Conference |Division=North |ShortConference=Big 12 |CoachRank=5 |APRank=4 |BCSRank=<!-- No final BCS Poll --> |Record=12&ndash;2 |ConfRecord=7&ndash;1 |HeadCoach=[[Gary Pinkel]] |OffCoach=[[Dave Christensen]] |DefCoach=[[Matt Eberflus]] |OScheme=[[Spread offense|Spread]] |DScheme=[[4â3 defense|4â3]] |StadiumArena=[[Faurot Field]] (c. 68,174) |Champion=Big 12 North Co-Champions |BowlTourney=[[2008 Cotton Bowl Classic|AT&T Cotton Bowl Classic]] vs. [[2007 Arkansas Razorbacks football team|Arkansas]] |BowlTourneyResult=W 38&ndash;7 |ConfChamp = [[2007 Big 12 Championship Game|Big 12 Championship]] vs. [[2007 Oklahoma Sooners football team|Oklahoma]] |ConfChampResult = L 17&ndash;38 }} {{2007 Big 12 football standings}} The '''2007 [[Missouri Tigers]] [[Missouri Tigers football|football team]]''' represented the [[University of Missouri]] in [[college football|college football's]] [[2007 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2007 season]]. The team was coached by [[Gary Pinkel]] and played their home games at [[Faurot Field|Faurot Field at Memorial Stadium]].
The team was led by junior [[quarterback]] [[Chase Daniel]], a [[Heisman Trophy]] candidate<ref>[http://www.columbiamissourian.com/stories/2007/11/17/chase-heisman-web-site-debuts/ "Chase the Heisman" web-site debuts] ''Columbia-Missourian'', 17 November 2007.</ref><ref>Grillo, Ron. [http://www.rockymounttelegram.com/sports/content/sports/stories/2007/11/1119/Grillo.html?cxtype=rss&cxsvc=7&cxcat=13 Heisman chase will continue from field to New York] ''Rocky Mountain Telegram'', 19 November 2007.</ref><ref>Watson, Graham. [http://www.stltoday.com/stltoday/sports/stories.nsf/mizzou/story/6A76850EC081A6538625739300155969?OpenDocument As ballots go out, Daniel is on Heisman Trophy list] ''St. Louis Post-Dispatch'', 14 November 2007.</ref><ref>[http://www.sportsline.com/collegefootball/heisman NCAA football Heisman hopefuls]</ref> who finished fourth in voting behind [[Tim Tebow]], [[Darren McFadden]], and [[Colt Brennan]]. In the preseason, the Tigers were picked by some to win the Big 12 North.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Steele |first=Phil |year=2007 |title=Big 12 Conference |journal=Phil Steele's 2007 College Football Preview |volume=13 |pages=80â81 }}</ref>
On November 24, Missouri won their 11th game of the season by beating their arch-rival [[Kansas Jayhawks football|Kansas Jayhawks]] 36-28, in the [[Border Showdown]] at [[Arrowhead Stadium]] in [[Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City]]. The game sealed Mizzou's first Big 12 North division title and earned them an inaugural trip to the [[Big 12 Football Championship Game|Big 12 Championship Game]] against the [[Oklahoma Sooners football|Oklahoma Sooners]] on December 1.
Until the Big 12 Championship game, the Tigers were the only team in college football to have scored at least 30 points in every game.
The Tigers won over 9 games in a season for the first time since 1969, and were ranked #1 in the [[AP Poll]] for the first time since 1960.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/news/story?id=3127118 | title=Not since 1960 has Missouri held down poll's No. 1 ranking | publisher=Associated Press | date=2007-11-25 | accessdate=2007-11-25}}</ref> This ranking lead to the tigers first ever appearance on the cover of sports illustrated magazine. The Tigers also achieved their highest [[Bowl Championship Series|BCS]] ranking in history, at #1 after the Border Showdown.
After losing the Big 12 Championship game 38-17 to the Sooners, Missouri was chosen to play [[2007 Arkansas Razorbacks football team|Arkansas]] in the [[2008 Cotton Bowl Classic|Cotton Bowl Classic]].
Five Tiger starters were named to the Associated Press All-American teams. Senior Tight End [[Martin Rucker (football)|Martin Rucker]] and Freshman Wide Receiver [[Jeremy Maclin]] (as an All-Purpose player) were named as first team selections, while Junior Quarterback [[Chase Daniel]] and Junior Safety [[William Moore (football)|William Moore]] were named to the second team. Senior Center [[Adam Spieker]] was a third team selection. [http://mutigers.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/121107aab.html]
